# Solving the Matching Augment Problem in Lean 4

We need to prove that if a graph `G` has a matching `M` which is not maximum, then there exists an augmenting path with respect to `M`. An augmenting path is a path where the first and last vertices are not in `V(G, M)` (the set of vertices covered by `M`), and every other vertex in the path is in `V(G, M)`. 

First, let's think about how to construct such a path. Since `M` is not maximum, there exists another matching `M'` such that `|M'| > |M|`. Consider the symmetric difference `M' Δ M`. This is the set of edges that are in either `M'` or `M` but not in both. The graph `G' = G[ M' Δ M ]` (the subgraph of `G` induced by the symmetric difference) will have vertices from `V(G, M)` and `V(G, M')`. 

Since `M` and `M'` are matchings, the degree of any vertex in `G'` will be at most 2 (each vertex can be matched by at most one edge from `M` and at most one edge from `M'`). Moreover, `G'` will be a disjoint union of cycles and paths. Each cycle must alternate between edges from `M` and `M'`. Since `|M'| > |M|`, there must be at least one path in `G'` that starts and ends at vertices not in `V(G, M)` (i.e., vertices matched by `M'` but not by `M`). This path will be an augmenting path for `M`.

